You should decide to either stick to just blocking or just asynchronous. I recommend keeping it asynchronous and using [`submit()`][1] to avoid nested callbacks:

```java
user.openPrivateChannel().submit() // CompletableFuture&lt;PrivateChannel&gt;
    .thenCompose((channel) -&gt; {
        channel.sendMessage(ignored).queue();
        return channel.sendMessage(embed).submit(); // CompletableFuture&lt;Message&gt;
    })
    .thenCompose((message) -&gt; CompletableFuture.allOf( // combine 2 futures to 1
        message.addReaction(a).submit(),
        message.addReaction(b).submit())) // CompletableFuture&lt;Void&gt;
    .whenComplete((v, error) -&gt; {
        if (error != null) error.printStackTrace(); // handle errors
    });
```

As correctly pointed out by Max Vollmer, you can&#39;t use `complete()` inside of a `queue()` callback because it will deadlock the thread of the callback. `complete()` works by running on the same thread used to handle the callback which is currently busy waiting for the complete call to finish which is waiting on the queue callback to finish, this is an endless cycle that will never be completed. [\[1\]][2]

[1]: https://ci.dv8tion.net/job/JDA/javadoc/net/dv8tion/jda/api/requests/RestAction.html#submit()
[2]: https://github.com/DV8FromTheWorld/JDA/wiki/19%29-Troubleshooting#preventing-use-of-complete-in-callback-threads

