You&#39;ll need to save the type of the first element first, then use `.every` to compare every other `typeof` against that:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function allSameType(arr) {
      const type = typeof arr[0];
      return arr.slice(1).every(item =&gt; type === typeof item);
    }
    const c = [1, 2, 3];
    const d = [1, 2, 3, &quot;4&quot;];
    console.log(allSameType(c));
    console.log(allSameType(d));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You are trying to access the first element passed in the `allSameType` as an array, but it is not the array but an element of the array.

You can pass the array to the `allSameType()` function as a third parameter, because the `Array.prototype.every` callback accepts three arguments:

1. The element (`i`)
2. The index of the element (`_`)
3. The array itself on which it is invoked. (`arr`)

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function allSameType(i, _, arr) {
       return (typeof i === typeof arr[0]);
    }
    const c = [1, 2, 3];
    const d = [1, 2, 3, &quot;4&quot;];
    console.log(c.every(allSameType));
    console.log(d.every(allSameType));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can use destructuring to get the 1st item (`first`), and the rest (`rest`), and then compare them with `Array.every()`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const allSameType = ([first, ...rest]) =&gt;
        rest.every(item =&gt; typeof item === typeof first)

    const c = [1, 2, 3];
    const d = [1, 2, 3, &quot;4&quot;];

    console.log(allSameType(c));
    console.log(allSameType(d));

