You should **not** be converting the columns to string and then parsing them. You should read them directly as the type they are.

```
consumable.Speed = (double) dataReader[&quot;SPEED&quot;];
```
or 
```
consumable.Speed = Convert.ToDouble(dataReader[&quot;SPEED&quot;]);
```

### Note on `null` handling

*(Thanks @mjwills for mentioning this)*

The results from the db may contain null values and there are many ways of handling nulls in results with `IDataReader` (you can see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1772025/sql-data-reader-handling-null-column-values or https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2609875/null-safe-way-to-get-values-from-an-idatareader or search the broader web).

For example you will need to decide if you want `null` or default value (0 for `double`) when the return value is null.

To get you started here&#39;s a helper method (which can easily be changed into a extension method, and maybe even made generic so that you can deal with `int`s and other types).

```
public static double GetNotNullExample(IDataReader reader, string colName, double valueIfNull)
{
    var colIndex = reader.GetOrdinal(colName);
    if (!reader.IsDBNull(colIndex))
        return reader.GetDouble(colIndex);
    else
        return valueIfNull;
}
```


